					<physDesc rend="visible">
						<p>Parchment codex of the 15th century.</p>
						<objectDesc form="codex">
							<supportDesc material="perg">
								<support>Parchment.</support>
								<extent>424 folios<dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
										<height>205</height>
										<width>140</width>
									</dimensions>
									<dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
										<height>120</height>
										<width>75</width>
									</dimensions>
								</extent>
								<foliation>
									<p>424 folios (+ 2 modern unfoliated paper flyleaves at the beginning and 3 modern unfoliated paper flyleaves and 1 older parchment flyleaf at the end). Folios 1 and 2 are paper flyleaves.</p>
								</foliation>
								<collation>
									<p>Quires of mostly 10 leaves each.</p>
								</collation>
							</supportDesc>
							<layoutDesc>
								<layout columns="2 " ruledLines="24" writtenLines="24">
									<p>Uniform layout.</p>
									<p>Visible hard-point ruling.</p>
									<p>Hair side and flesh side distinguishable.</p>
									<p>Titles and inital words in larger characters. </p>
									<p>Catchwords from page to page, ornamented with pen and ink designs.</p>
									<p>Numerous maniculae.</p>
									<p>Marginal notes and additions.</p>
								</layout>
							</layoutDesc>
						</objectDesc>
						<handDesc hands="2">
							<summary>Sefardi square script, unpunctuated, of the 15th century.</summary>
							<handNote script="Hebrew" scope="sole">
								<p>
									<locus from="410r" to="424v"/>: written in an Italian semi-cursive script of the 16th century.</p>
							</handNote>
						</handDesc>
						<additions>
							<p>An English description of the manuscript, pasted on folio 1v.</p>
							<p>Shimshon Kohen Modon: inscribed, folio 3r.</p>
							<p>A medical recipe, folio 424v.</p>
							<p>Censored by <name type="person" role="censor">Dominico Irosolomitano</name>, Italian censor (active 1575-1624): inscribed with his name (folio 424v); see <ref target="Popper_1969" type="page">61</ref>, and appendix § 62-74. </p>
						</additions>
						<bindingDesc>
							<binding>
								<p> Post-1600. Red leather, gold tooled. Boxed.</p>
								<p>Spine: 'Maimonides. More Nebuchim, Etc. Hebrew. Brit. Mus. Harley Or. 5525.'</p>
							</binding>
						</bindingDesc>
					</physDesc>
					<history rend="visible">
						<origin notBefore="1400" notAfter="1499"/>
						<provenance>
							<p>
								<name type="place">Italy</name> (or France, S. ?)</p>
						</provenance>
						<acquisition>
							<date>1753</date>
							<p>The Harley Collection, formed by <name type="person" role="owner">Robert Harley</name> (b. 1661, d. 1724), 1st Earl of Oxford and Mortimer, politician, and <name type="person" role="owner">Edward Harley</name> (b. 1689, d. 1741), 2nd Earl of Oxford and Mortimer, book collector and patron of the arts; inscribed as usual by their librarian, Humfrey Wanley, ‘18 die January, A.D. 1723/4’ (folio 2r).
Edward Harley bequeathed the library to his widow, <name type="person" role="owner">Henrietta Cavendish, née Holles</name> (b. 1694, d. 1755) during her lifetime and thereafter to their daughter, <name type="person" role="owner">Margaret Cavendish Bentinck</name> (b. 1715, d.1785), Duchess of Portland; the manuscripts were sold by the Countess and the Duchess in 1753 to the nation for £10,000 (a fraction of their contemporary value) under the Act of Parliament that also established the British Museum; the Harley manuscripts form one of the foundation collections of the British Library.</p>
						</acquisition>
